{"term":"1972","caseName":"National Association for the Advancement of Colored People v. New York","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1972/72-129","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - February 28, 1973","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/16724","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"You may resume, you have about nine minutes left.","start":0,"stop":8.751,"duration":8.75}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":8.751,"stop":10.952,"duration":2.2},{"text":"As I was discussing yesterday, the only issue in this case is did the District Court earned denying intervention in April 19, 1972 in light of the circumstances existing at that time in light of the allegations before it.","start":10.952,"stop":23.948,"duration":13},{"text":"Under Rule 24 (a), the application for intervention must be timely it is a requirement of the rule.","start":23.948,"stop":29.907,"duration":5.96},{"text":"We think this is particularly important on Section 4 (a) cases where time may in fact be of the essence.","start":29.907,"stop":36.037,"duration":6.13},{"text":"Congress itself recognize this by assigning these cases to three Judge District Courts and allowing for direct appeal to this Court.","start":36.037,"stop":42.782,"duration":6.74},{"text":"Now here appellants file their motion to intervene on April 7.","start":42.782,"stop":46.614,"duration":3.83},{"text":"The action itself have been filed by the State of New York in December 3rd. More then four months had passed since the action had originally been filed, the Justice Department had been investigating New York’s complaint during this time and had completed his investigation.","start":46.614,"stop":61.588,"duration":14.97},{"text":"In the District Court, at this time the only explanation, appellants gave to the District Court for filing the action at this time is contained on page 47 of the appendix.","start":61.588,"stop":74.391,"duration":12.8},{"text":"I read from their motion to intervene, paragraph six, “because counsel for petitioners was only informed within the last 48 hours, the United States would not adequately represent the interest of petitioners and because substantial litigation has not yet occurred.","start":74.391,"stop":91.463,"duration":17.07},{"text":"The instant application is to intervene is timely.","start":91.463,"stop":95.325,"duration":3.86},{"text":"As against this, New York objected to the intervention and their objections are contained on page 67 to 70 of the appendix.","start":95.325,"stop":106.976,"duration":11.65},{"text":"New York pointed out four basic things, number one; the action had been pending for four months.","start":106.976,"stop":112.99,"duration":6.01},{"text":"Number two, appellants or applicants at the time there before the District Court were clearly on notice of this case.","start":112.99,"stop":121.279,"duration":8.29},{"text":"The affidavit pointed to a New York Times article where political leaders in this counties were discussing whether to intervene or whether to take action with respect to New York’s complaint the fact that in the article itself which is reprinted in the reply brief of the appellants here also mentioned that a citizens voter education committee chairman had not mentioned the action.","start":121.279,"stop":144.027,"duration":22.75},{"text":"The other point that New York made is that intervention at this time would disrupt and possibly preclude New York’s upcoming primary elections where delegates to the democratic national convention would be chosen, where delegates to the state assembly and the state senate and congressional seats would be chosen.","start":144.027,"stop":160.568,"duration":16.54},{"text":"The reasons it would have that effect is because New York had agreed that this is reapportion and is covered by Section 5, unless New York got out from the Act under 4 (a), Section 5 would remain outstanding and then they would have to go through the lengthy process of having clearance with the Attorney General which could not be completed by the time the elections were scheduled to be held.","start":160.568,"stop":183.187,"duration":22.62},{"text":"The fourth point and form the Department of Justice’s point of view and we think the most important that New York made is that at no time, during this period that the appellants offer any evidence to the Department of Justice regarding why New York was not entitled to summary judgment.","start":183.187,"stop":200.465,"duration":17.28},{"text":"Now this is what was before the District Court, these are the allegations that were before the District Court and of course the District Court denied intervention at that time.","start":200.465,"stop":209.94,"duration":9.47},{"text":"And we think that the Court acted within its discretion.","start":209.94,"stop":212.983,"duration":3.04},{"text":"The only other case dealing with intervention in the section 4 (a) case which is very close to this case is the Apache County case which we’ve sited and discussed beginning on page 22 of our brief.","start":212.983,"stop":225.467,"duration":12.48},{"text":"Judge Leventhal speaking for the Court in that case in discussing intervention said that in these kinds of cases, the applicants must at least first and I quote “bring to the attention of the Department of Justice any instances of discrimination in the use of literacy test.","start":225.467,"stop":244.995,"duration":19.53},{"text":"The appellants have not done so here and in fact just about a year and half before they sought to intervene they go into record indicating that in fact they had no such evidence.","start":244.995,"stop":255.804,"duration":10.81},{"text":"I read from the 1969 hearings on the extension of the Voting’s Right Act and Clarence Mitchell’s testimony before the house judiciary committee to chairman of manual seller have used—","start":255.804,"stop":269.49,"duration":13.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this something the District Court would consider?","start":269.49,"stop":272.381,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No it’s not, it’s not.","start":272.381,"stop":275.808,"duration":3.43},{"text":"I am trying to indicate why, a possible explanation why no evidence was presented to the Justice Department.","start":275.808,"stop":282.392,"duration":6.58},{"text":"This is on record, I am reading from pages 251 to 252, the hearings which is cited throughout appellants brief.","start":282.392,"stop":290.093,"duration":7.7},{"text":"Chairman seller have used one of the principle officials of the national association for the advancement of colored people had any appreciable complaints from parts of the country other than those southern states which indicate that there are abuses of the type you have mentioned here.","start":290.093,"stop":303.013,"duration":12.92},{"text":"Mr. Mitchell, the answer to that question Mr. Chairman is no, it goes on to say, “I would further state that I would check with the general council the NAACP legal defense and education fund Mr. Greenburg, may I ask for his permission to quote him to the said committee?”","start":303.013,"stop":317.307,"duration":14.29},{"text":"He said “we have not any cases in the long history of our organization involving denial of the right to vote for literacy reasons outside the southern states of this country.","start":317.307,"stop":326.24,"duration":8.93},{"text":"We have very little litigation on the question of voting in states other than those covered by the 65 Act.","start":326.24,"stop":331.714,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well how far outside the record can we go in reviewing the District Court’s decision?","start":331.714,"stop":337.618,"duration":5.9}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that you should state exactly within the record Mr. Justice.","start":337.618,"stop":343.254,"duration":5.64},{"text":"I site this because there has been an awful lot of testimony cited on the other side about what other people said during the 1969 hearings.","start":343.254,"stop":349.314,"duration":6.06},{"text":"I am trying to set kind of the atmosphere that was present at the time when New York instituted this suite, what people concerned with this questions thought about.","start":349.314,"stop":358.735,"duration":9.42},{"text":"We had allegations in the case that well -- we were interested in this case all along and no one came to us, to ask us in our view of the case.","start":358.735,"stop":366.089,"duration":7.35},{"text":"In fact, that is not entirely accurate but the point is that for four months nothing was done while the Justice Department was investigating the case and we think that it’s a particular appropriate requirement for intervention in these kinds of cases and the Court in the Apache County.","start":366.089,"stop":382.538,"duration":16.45},{"text":"So help that the applicants ought to first come to the Justice Department who is investigating the case and present it with the evidence that they have of discriminatory use of literacy test.","start":382.538,"stop":393.168,"duration":10.63},{"text":"In fact I think if you remember the argument of my colleague here yesterday, that is exactly what they are going to do with respect to the section five actions.","start":393.168,"stop":402.533,"duration":9.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Does necessarily all of your argument what they can do and what term?","start":402.533,"stop":409.659,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right, that is right.","start":409.659,"stop":411.139,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now would you say it was the time that goes the election?","start":411.139,"stop":416.342,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, I think that --","start":416.342,"stop":417.559,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it wasn’t necessary to enjoin the election or anything in anyway to make a conviction.","start":417.559,"stop":425.945,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t believe that seems Justice, I will try to explain why.","start":425.945,"stop":428.909,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Why, I would suppose that everything that the Court have authority to what some election proceed under some statute that might be unconstitutional.","start":428.909,"stop":442.769,"duration":13.86}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"First of all, the first point I would like to make is that that was not suggested to the District Court, in fact --","start":442.769,"stop":448.949,"duration":6.18}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that make a difference?","start":448.949,"stop":450.393,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I’m trying to set the stages to what was before the District Court in the basis.","start":450.393,"stop":454.238,"duration":3.85},{"text":"Second of all, the way the Voting Rights Act is framed, changes in voting cannot be implemented until they have been cleared by the Attorney General.","start":454.238,"stop":466.317,"duration":12.08},{"text":"Now the changes --","start":466.317,"stop":467.593,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That that decision would still had to be made is to whether this distinct was properly subject.","start":467.593,"stop":474.998,"duration":7.4}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the only way that requirement could be forgotten is if the state got a section 4 (a) judgment removing it from coverage.","start":474.998,"stop":485.425,"duration":10.43},{"text":"The appellants wanted to intervene to prevent New York from getting the Section 4 (a) judgment.","start":485.425,"stop":491.47,"duration":6.05},{"text":"If without that Section 4 (a) judgment, if New York sought to implement and conduct its election and might I add at the time that all this was going on, nominating petitions were beginning to circulate.","start":491.47,"stop":503.231,"duration":11.76},{"text":"Candidates are beginning to organize campaigns and so on, if they had sought to implement those changes that would have been a violation of section 5 of the Voting Rights Act.","start":503.231,"stop":512.917,"duration":9.69},{"text":"Regardless of whether the appellants action in New York state which they had implemented had to go on forward or not, it would still be a violation of the Section because they could not implement those changes until or unless they have an outstanding 4 (a) judgment.","start":512.917,"stop":526.919,"duration":14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Pertaining to elections to need under statutes that the phrase are simply unconstitutional.","start":526.919,"stop":536.417,"duration":9.5}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well in Allan and I remember --","start":536.417,"stop":539.356,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe perhaps that -- I don’t know what do you suppose would happen?","start":539.356,"stop":542.346,"duration":2.99},{"text":"I suppose that the government would have consented to let the elections proceed.","start":542.346,"stop":547.971,"duration":5.63}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well on basis of hindsight, I suppose it would, I mean we certainly do not want to disrupt New York --","start":547.971,"stop":552.476,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You were consenting to take an alibi.","start":552.476,"stop":554.613,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":554.613,"stop":555.265,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What would the other side would have done you think?","start":555.265,"stop":558.269,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that if one reads the -- if one reads the motion to intervene which is contained on pages 44 to 47, that is the motion to intervene.","start":558.269,"stop":568.313,"duration":10.04},{"text":"There is not a word in there about which is supposed to under rule 24 (c), is supposed to contain the grounds for intervention.","start":568.313,"stop":575.229,"duration":6.92},{"text":"There is not a word in there about whether New York had used its literacy test discriminatorily which was the issue in this case.","start":575.229,"stop":582.619,"duration":7.39},{"text":"This entire motion to intervene is framed on the basis that we want to stop New York from having these elections.","start":582.619,"stop":589.943,"duration":7.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So you think that was really the medium, the motivation to file the motion?","start":589.943,"stop":592.893,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t see how anyone could reach any other conclusion if you read the motion to intervene.","start":592.893,"stop":597.751,"duration":4.86}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it your position because of the structure of the Voting Rights Act New York’s primaries could have gone ahead only if there was a final judgment form the District Court here exempted them from the coverage?","start":597.751,"stop":609.78,"duration":12.03}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Or in the alternative if they had gotten clearance from the Attorney General but the process of getting clearance that appellants have suggested that well we could -- they could have gotten expedited.","start":609.78,"stop":621.554,"duration":11.77},{"text":"The regulation that they site in their reply brief says essentially the Justice Department will do the best it can but the point is if it takes 50 or 40 or 60 days to investigate redistricting in New York City then nothing can happen during that period of time.","start":621.554,"stop":637.324,"duration":15.77},{"text":"I mean the State of New York can’t pass unqualified candidates and this has an effect -- more like a domino effect throughout the state.","start":637.324,"stop":645.125,"duration":7.8},{"text":"If you pull out three of the congressional districts for example, involving -- or the congressional districts in Kings County, New York County and Bronx County that has a snow balling effect throughout the state because they are not done on county lines.","start":645.125,"stop":658.636,"duration":13.51},{"text":"You have pull them out and you have affect Richmond, you affect Westchester.","start":658.636,"stop":661.906,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you if -- under the statute because you are obligated to consent to entry of judgment here unless you have some reason to believe this tested and used.","start":661.906,"stop":675.603,"duration":13.7}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":675.603,"stop":677.234,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, isn’t that very likely burden you have or the authority you have or the directions you have under Section 5 when something is presented to you.","start":677.234,"stop":689.66,"duration":12.43}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Very close, the issues are different.","start":689.66,"stop":692.515,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well what is the issue how is the issue different?","start":692.515,"stop":693.685,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In Section 5 the question is whether to change in voting that has just been implemented is discriminatory on racial grounds in voting.","start":693.685,"stop":702.39,"duration":8.71},{"text":"In section 4 (a) the question is --","start":702.39,"stop":703.848,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I will put it to you this way, if you consent to the entry of judgment in a suit such as we have here.","start":703.848,"stop":711.899,"duration":8.05}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":711.899,"stop":712.743,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Wouldn’t you have passed the New York law if it had been submitted to you?","start":712.743,"stop":717.166,"duration":4.42}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t think that follows at all Mr. Justice.","start":717.166,"stop":719.043,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it doesn’t.","start":719.043,"stop":719.877,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because the issue in this case is why the literacy tests in the past ten years used to discriminate on the basis of race.","start":719.877,"stop":729.399,"duration":9.52},{"text":"The question in Section 5 cases is has --","start":729.399,"stop":732.466,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the new statute.","start":732.466,"stop":732.953,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the new statute going to discriminate on the basis of race.","start":732.953,"stop":737.219,"duration":4.27},{"text":"Now I would hold that a state would get out from under Section 5 and not to section 4 and not go back to --","start":737.219,"stop":743.242,"duration":6.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"At least it’s very unlikely that you would consent into one case and hold them up and hold the law.","start":743.242,"stop":749.438,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be unlikely only for the reason that if a state is not discriminated in the use of its literacy test can one conclude that it would not discriminate on the basis of districts that it draws.","start":749.438,"stop":759.76,"duration":10.32},{"text":"I don’t know whether that’s a valid conclusion.","start":759.76,"stop":763.601,"duration":3.84},{"text":"For these reasons, we think that the District Court acted within its discretion as we said before we did not object to the motion to intervene, after the motion to intervene was denied.","start":763.601,"stop":776.927,"duration":13.33},{"text":"We looked at the case and we believed that they acted within their discretion in denying at that time, thank you.","start":776.927,"stop":781.012,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What is your fundamental reason for saying that not as in intervention as a bright as compared with --","start":781.012,"stop":788.451,"duration":7.44}]},{"speakerName":"A. Raymond Randolph, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in the first place, the individual appellants in this case were five -- are five people only from Kings County New York.","start":788.451,"stop":797.635,"duration":9.18},{"text":"None of them claim to be voting --victims of voting discrimination.","start":797.635,"stop":801.064,"duration":3.43},{"text":"All of them in fact say they are dully qualified voters.","start":801.064,"stop":804.166,"duration":3.1},{"text":"The organization represented is the NAACP which is the 18 branches of the NAACP in New York City.","start":804.166,"stop":811.64,"duration":7.47},{"text":"What they are purporting to represent Mr. Justice is simply the right of minority groups not to be discriminated on the basis of race but that’s precisely what the Attorney General is charged with representing under the Act.","start":811.64,"stop":824.167,"duration":12.53},{"text":"We don’t think their interest is any different from the Attorney General, that is to represent the public interest.","start":824.167,"stop":829.909,"duration":5.74},{"text":"Now I know if only one case really where an intervener has been allowed to come in to represent the public interest and that is the El Paso case.","start":829.909,"stop":837.659,"duration":7.75},{"text":"If that case is not restricted, if it’s not restricted to situations where the Government has violated or prior mandated the Court then we would agree that in certain circumstance, we think that people can come in to intervene as a right in Voting Rights Act cases.","start":837.659,"stop":856.097,"duration":18.44},{"text":"I mean we would have no other choice but to say that but we think that as a prerequisite they ought to at least submit evidence to the Department of Justice which is investigating the matter and say “look, this is why we think New York are entitled to a 4 (a) judgment.”","start":856.097,"stop":868.617,"duration":12.52},{"text":"We don’t think that a person should be allowed that just simply sit back, have the evidence, wait for the government to complete its investigation, wait push it all the way to the moment before primary elections were going to be held and then suddenly say “Hey, we have this evidence and we don’t think New York is entitled to the summary judgment it seeks.”","start":868.617,"stop":884.957,"duration":16.34},{"text":"We think they ought to have an obligation to come in earlier and present us with it that is what appellants are going to do under their Section 5 submission.","start":884.957,"stop":892.727,"duration":7.77},{"text":"Mr. Greenburg mentioned that yesterday that the first step is they were going to present the government with the submission about why, thank you.","start":892.727,"stop":902.105,"duration":9.38}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well, Mr. Attorney General.","start":902.105,"stop":910.481,"duration":8.38}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and May it please the Court.","start":910.481,"stop":913.645,"duration":3.16},{"text":"I’d like to begin on this climate as question as trying to explain the serious harm that the state of New York would have faced if the delayed intervention of the applicants had been allowed in this case.","start":913.645,"stop":927.451,"duration":13.81},{"text":"To understand this you have to begin with the fact that to no fault of its own, the state of New York was not supplied with a complete set of census statistics by the United States Bureau of the Census until October 15, 1971 and it was only after that date that the state could begin the task of during a 150 new assembly districts.","start":927.451,"stop":952.263,"duration":24.81},{"text":"60 new State Senate Districts and then subsequently 39 new Congressional Districts, now it was recognized that a time involved in this and during this districts based on the principle of one man one vote which would characterize county lines could not be completed before the early part of 1972 at the earliest.","start":952.263,"stop":971.921,"duration":19.66},{"text":"And the state feared that a lengthy process involved in getting this clear through the Justice Department might delay the applicability of these new districts in the 1972 elections and thus the section 4 (a) suit was commenced.","start":971.921,"stop":987.284,"duration":15.36},{"text":"As it turned out our fears were realized since the assembly in senate districting statute was enacted on January 14, 1972.","start":987.284,"stop":997.918,"duration":10.63},{"text":"It was submitted pursuant to Section 5 on January 24.","start":997.918,"stop":1003.622,"duration":5.7},{"text":"We did not hear anything further from the Justice Department and so more than seven weeks later when on March 14 we received a letter saying that they wanted further information particularly demographic information as to the population and registration by race and by Puerto Rican ancestry in each of a districts in the three effective counties.","start":1003.622,"stop":1025.007,"duration":21.39},{"text":"I may add that information as to registration is not supplied by the Census Bureau, this requires extra information which would have taken weeks to complete.","start":1025.007,"stop":1034.164,"duration":9.16},{"text":"And therefore when we come to the date of April 7, when appellants are first seeking to intervene, any delay at that point would have caused chaos in the electoral processes in the state of New York.","start":1034.164,"stop":1047.435,"duration":13.27},{"text":"On April the 4th, the fist date for circulating petitions for the spring primary had already commenced.","start":1047.435,"stop":1055.445,"duration":8.01},{"text":"Without section 4 (a) judgments, all this new lines would have been subject to an injunction.","start":1055.445,"stop":1062.359,"duration":6.91},{"text":"As a matter of fact, the appellants at the same time if they filed a suite in Washington had filed a suit in the Southern District of New York to halt the elections under the new assembly senate and the congressional district lines.","start":1062.359,"stop":1076.321,"duration":13.96},{"text":"Now what would have happened, we would have to go back to the old districts which were based on population figures on the 1960 census that were 12 years out of date.","start":1076.321,"stop":1088.716,"duration":12.39},{"text":"Now against the serious harm that the State of New York would have suffered by this delay intervention, what do appellants’ papers show?","start":1088.716,"stop":1098.382,"duration":9.67},{"text":"Do they show thousands of cases in which individuals have been discriminated against in the application of a literacy test?","start":1098.382,"stop":1105.357,"duration":6.97},{"text":"No, they don’t even show a single instance in which any New Yorker has been discriminated in a conduct of a literacy tests.","start":1105.357,"stop":1116.887,"duration":11.53},{"text":"Apparently the thing that appellants are most worried about is their claim that the new congressional lines might have been based on racial gerrymandering.","start":1116.887,"stop":1126.677,"duration":9.79},{"text":"They site no specific evidence for this but even if this was the case, there is no reason why they could have not bought a Civil Rights Action under section 1983 in the District Courts of New York and trying to prove their case as would have been Dominic as we know from the Gamelan case and Wright v. Rockefeller has been done into many other instances.","start":1126.677,"stop":1147.396,"duration":20.72},{"text":"Instead what they are really trying to do is take the easy way out by a Section 5 action where you don’t have to prove discrimination, all you have to prove is that the state did not comply with the clearance procedures of Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act.","start":1147.396,"stop":1169.892,"duration":22.5},{"text":"May I remind the Court that in the case of South Carolina versus Katzenbach, at that the time the State of South Carolina was attacking the constitutionality of the Voting Rights Act of 1965 in a particular Section 4 and 5 and they made the argument that these sections were unconstitutional because for a state to prove the lack of discrimination would involve an almost impossible burden since it is very difficult to prove a negative of a proposition rather than the positive.","start":1169.892,"stop":1202.618,"duration":32.73},{"text":"This Court answered that contention while relying primarily on the testimony of the Attorney General Katzenbach and said “all the state need do is submit affidavits from their voting officials attesting to the fact that there has been no discrimination in a conduct of literacy test and man answer any evidence that the Justice Department might uncover during the course of their investigation and that was the situation here.","start":1202.618,"stop":1230.43,"duration":27.81},{"text":"That is what the State of New York did, they submitted to the District Court every literacy test that was given with in the past ten years and they submitted affidavits from election officials to show that not only did New York City just sit back and waited people to came to it to register.","start":1230.43,"stop":1248.832,"duration":18.4},{"text":"On the contrary, since 1964 the board of elections of the City of New York has sent mobile registration units into the heart of the inner city areas, into the areas where there was a high density of black population and through the use of sound trucks have encourage people to come to register and vote.","start":1248.832,"stop":1269.095,"duration":20.26},{"text":"I dare say, I know of no other city in the country which is that as much that try to encourage minority citizens to vote and therefore we feel that this particular action is particularly unfair that is the consequences of Section 4 based on a purely statistical presumption which we believe we have rebutted.","start":1269.095,"stop":1292.874,"duration":23.78},{"text":"Now at appellant’s briefs, before this Court although there was no evidence presented by them to the District Court, they have tried to draw an analogy to the Guest and County case, trying to argue that if you can prove educational inequality in New York you can somehow try to raise an argument of discrimination in the conduct of a literacy test.","start":1292.874,"stop":1318.229,"duration":25.36},{"text":"But in the Gaston case can be easily distinguished from the situation in New York.","start":1318.229,"stop":1323.438,"duration":5.21},{"text":"First of all in Gaston, no matter what the educational background of a person was, he had to pass the literacy test even if he has a PHD degree.","start":1323.438,"stop":1334.462,"duration":11.02},{"text":"In the state of New York prior to 1965, if you completed eight grades of school and since 1965 if you only completed six grades of school, you did not have to take a literacy test.","start":1334.462,"stop":1348.634,"duration":14.17},{"text":"So even if they could show us and we do not believe they could that there was inequality in various schools in the city of New York, this is irrelevant since anyone who has completed six grades of school would not have to take a literacy test.","start":1348.634,"stop":1363.42,"duration":14.79},{"text":"It is also been shown that throughout the ten year period leading up to the institution of this action, less than 5% of those who took the literacy test failed it.","start":1363.42,"stop":1381.153,"duration":17.73},{"text":"Appellants have also tried to raise an argument that Congress in enacting the 1970 Amendments of the Voting Rights Act sought to include New York State because of some evidence of discrimination and yet nothing in the record of Congress in the hearings of a 1970 extensions points to this thing.","start":1381.153,"stop":1401.796,"duration":20.64},{"text":"The purpose of the 1970 Amendment and using 1968 as a standard was simply because it would be illogical to extend the acts protection for an additional five years without updating the date of the election which would serve as the standard in measuring voter participation.","start":1401.796,"stop":1419.079,"duration":17.28},{"text":"Not because of any evidence that could have been any discrimination in New York State and indeed as the Solicitor General has pointed out, Clarence Mitchell when his testimony for the house Judiciary committee admitted that he had no evidence of any discrimination in New York State.","start":1419.079,"stop":1437.073,"duration":17.99},{"text":"Now one other argument, I would just like to point to one of the question of the remand, it has been lightly assumed that there would be no dire consequences if this thing was remanded to the District Court to take further testimony.","start":1437.073,"stop":1448.956,"duration":11.88},{"text":"May I point out that if the judgment below was vacated, we would now have a cloud of doubt as to the validity of all the existing assembly senate and congressional districts?","start":1448.956,"stop":1461.195,"duration":12.24},{"text":"More than that in this past year, we had a new counsel statute adopted for the city of New York.","start":1461.195,"stop":1467.171,"duration":5.98},{"text":"33 new counsel somatic districts which would have not ever been cleared across by the Justice Department and therefore all this new council somatic districts for this year’s election would be subject to an injunction.","start":1467.171,"stop":1479.001,"duration":11.83},{"text":"In addition, al the election laws that have been passed including the run off provisions for the mayor election of New York city this year would be subject to a Section 5 injunction and therefore we view the consequences of a remand as posing continues chaos in the electoral processes in the State of New York, thank you.","start":1479.001,"stop":1502.287,"duration":23.29}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Greenburg.","start":1502.287,"stop":1503.367,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and May it please the Court.","start":1503.367,"stop":1505.426,"duration":2.06},{"text":"In reply I would like to touch on several points.","start":1505.426,"stop":1508.615,"duration":3.19},{"text":"The first is timeliness and apparently the time the appropriateness of the time is being measured by two ways.","start":1508.615,"stop":1515.526,"duration":6.91},{"text":"In the assumptions that counsel respondents are making as to what was the reason for the District Court judgment which it never articulated.","start":1515.526,"stop":1522.835,"duration":7.31},{"text":"First as to the time and which we filed after the Government’s position became manifest, we filed within two days after learning it and four days after filing it, I can’t imagine anyone doing anything speedier.","start":1522.835,"stop":1534.32,"duration":11.48},{"text":"Secondly as to the time before the primary election, counsel for the Government has referred to our action being on the eve of the primary.","start":1534.32,"stop":1542.014,"duration":7.69},{"text":"In fact it was 74 days in advance of the primary and I submit that any Court can tell counsel that if you want to intervene in this case and you want to have your hearing, get your case in within so many days of the week and go on with the primary, we will make other arrangements if necessary and counsel would have been ready and willing to do and of course do that sort of thing all the time.","start":1542.014,"stop":1559.997,"duration":17.98}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When do you have to file?","start":1559.997,"stop":1562.136,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"When do we have to file what?","start":1562.136,"stop":1562.908,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"When you are in the primary you are on one of the districts you are going to --","start":1562.908,"stop":1565.96,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct Mr. Justice --","start":1565.96,"stop":1567.543,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well when was the filing date?","start":1567.543,"stop":1569.014,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"The filing date I believe was considerably earlier, it was on April 4.","start":1569.014,"stop":1575.476,"duration":6.46}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":1575.476,"stop":1576.829,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"And we filed our application for intervention I think April 4th or 5th but the two could have go on simultaneously was illegal the Court then could have taken some appropriate measures to deal with that.","start":1576.829,"stop":1588.703,"duration":11.87},{"text":"Either as you suggested in your question, let things stand for the time being or order some alternative procedures to be decided.","start":1588.703,"stop":1595.762,"duration":7.06},{"text":"The case could have been decided in a matter of days or weeks.","start":1595.762,"stop":1598.407,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you that sure Mr. Greenburg that short of a final judgment by the District of Columbia Court that New York didn’t have to comply, that it could have granted some sort of intern permission for it not to comply?","start":1598.407,"stop":1614.698,"duration":16.29}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"New York was indeed proceeding at that time and it did not yet have a final judgment.","start":1614.698,"stop":1618.334,"duration":3.64},{"text":"New York had been proceeding since at least a month earlier with the filing of petitions and getting them out and so forth, so New York was that sure and obviously they were going on ahead with it.","start":1618.334,"stop":1628.977,"duration":10.64},{"text":"If their procedures have been validated and I submit that there are proposed answer and our motion goal to judgment and the material submitted indicate that we would have won that case if we were permitted to intervene.","start":1628.977,"stop":1639.896,"duration":10.92}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What was New York’s approach if they did not need to submit?","start":1639.896,"stop":1644.304,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"New York’s approach was that they had not used the -- they had urged that they had not used the literacy test for ten years earlier with the purpose or the effective rights of discrimination.","start":1644.304,"stop":1656.562,"duration":12.26}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So coverage wasn’t--","start":1656.562,"stop":1658.296,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Right but --","start":1658.296,"stop":1659.283,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So the coverage was not automatically intermittent but on it, to buy its terms they acted cover.","start":1659.283,"stop":1665.157,"duration":5.87}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes but they said they have not used the act with the purpose or the effect of racial discrimination, their only allegations, their only evidence was concerning effect and the evidence on effect if we are going to follow the Gaston County case was all on the paper and the census reports and various published reports which we have attached with our motion to over judge.","start":1665.157,"stop":1686.991,"duration":21.83},{"text":"So the timeliness thing live 74 days and there was many accord and still many litigant to get something settled in great deal short of time in 74 days and I submit if the Court have said that here and the parties haven’t complied they could have at that point denied intervention and not allowed the interveners to proceed further.","start":1686.991,"stop":1704.049,"duration":17.06},{"text":"None of that was -- there was no reason, it is just you can’t intervene; you can’t appear, that’s the only thing that was said.","start":1704.049,"stop":1710.654,"duration":6.61},{"text":"Secondly, there’s been some suggestion about standing here and we submit that the applicants here have precisely the same standing as any voter in any reapportionment case and indeed the standing of the applicants’ right in fortune is they have additional standing that they are office holders, they are state assembly men.","start":1710.654,"stop":1730.649,"duration":19.99},{"text":"They are asserting the public interest I guess as any litigant does in a constitutional case and even far more than that they’re asserting their own personal interest and it has always been vindicated recognized by the court.","start":1730.649,"stop":1743.263,"duration":12.61}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Your suggestion now Mr. Greenburg that the Court must always write an opinion explaining when it acts in a situation like this?","start":1743.263,"stop":1750.818,"duration":7.56}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I said that obviously the Courts --","start":1750.818,"stop":1752.809,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe they thought the appeal or maybe they thought the motion was frivolous.","start":1752.809,"stop":1757.934,"duration":5.13}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well perhaps they might have, I think that we have to look at the objective record that we have before us and we will submit on the assertions here was not frivolous, it was quite serious and the litigants were serious litigants where state office holders and voters.","start":1757.934,"stop":1776.243,"duration":18.31},{"text":"The counsel or the counsel that the Courts were familiar with and not with anyone who is acting on a frivolous manner and then considerably at the allegations were serious and the serious exhibits were submitted in accord, along with the motion going through judgments so we just have to look at the papers we have before us to come to a conclusion as to what the Court may.","start":1776.243,"stop":1797.887,"duration":21.64},{"text":"As to the legislative history which Clarence Mitchell purports to quote me and I did quote me and that has been cited to the Court.","start":1797.887,"stop":1810.709,"duration":12.82},{"text":"I imagine that that was in a tactical situation of which he was arguing that the law should go forward, the Congress should go forward and pass the law and to cover only the south and not the north.","start":1810.709,"stop":1819.802,"duration":9.09},{"text":"Whatever Mr. Mitchell thought and whatever I thought of that moment, Congress thought otherwise and they have passed the law to cover the north as well as the south and indeed the very provision we are talking about is the Cooper Amendment and it just did not adventitiously touched upon New York.","start":1819.802,"stop":1831.85,"duration":12.05},{"text":"On page 19 of our brief Senator Cooper said “the chief state involvement of the state of New York, three candies of New York were involved Bronx, Kings and New York.","start":1831.85,"stop":1839.903,"duration":8.05},{"text":"In the 1964 election more than 50% of the voters are registered and more than 50% voted however for some reason in the 1968 election 50% were not registered of voting and so New York was not covered casually.”","start":1839.903,"stop":1853.437,"duration":13.53},{"text":"That is the intent of Congress and we submit that if the intent of Congress is not being carried out by a litigant in a lawsuit be it the United States or anyone else and that lawsuit will affect that party.","start":1853.437,"stop":1864.807,"duration":11.37},{"text":"Rule 24 quite explicitly provides that there maybe intervention that’s what the appellants attempted to do, that’s what they were not permitted to do.","start":1864.807,"stop":1873.442,"duration":8.63},{"text":"If being a matter of application or interventions as a right it should have been allowed and we submit the judgment below should be reversed.","start":1873.442,"stop":1879.92,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Greenburg, thank you gentlemen.","start":1879.92,"stop":1881.915,"duration":1.99},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":1881.915,"stop":1883.397,"duration":1.48}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - February 27, 1973","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/17113","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We’ll hear arguments next in 72-129, NAACP against New York and others.","start":0,"stop":36.506,"duration":36.51},{"text":"Mr. Greenberg.","start":36.506,"stop":38.506,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":38.506,"stop":41.293,"duration":2.79},{"text":"This case is here on appeal from the United States District Court for the District of Columbia which entered a judgment for the State of New York against the United States to which the United States consented and the judgment did two things.","start":41.293,"stop":56.592,"duration":15.3},{"text":"First, it exempted the State of New York from certain requirements of the Voting Rights Act of 1970, which I shall describe in more detail shortly.","start":56.592,"stop":66.902,"duration":10.31},{"text":"Briefly, the requirements from which the state was exempted were of two sorts.","start":66.902,"stop":70.94,"duration":4.04},{"text":"One, it was exempted from the necessity of pre-clearance of voting Law changes as required by Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act and secondly, it was allowed to restore its literacy tests earlier than otherwise would have been permitted under the Voting Rights Act of 1970.","start":70.94,"stop":89.592,"duration":18.65},{"text":"The judgment below also denied intervention to the appellants here when they attempted to enter the litigation to urge upon the Court that New York should remain subject to the provisions of the Voting Rights Act.","start":89.592,"stop":104.089,"duration":14.5},{"text":"In January and March 1970, New York redistricted its assembly, state senate and congressional districts.","start":104.089,"stop":112.784,"duration":8.7},{"text":"Appellants who are black and Puerto Rican citizens of New York City and the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People view the 1970 redistricting changes as an illegal racial gerrymander.","start":112.784,"stop":130.086,"duration":17.3},{"text":"They claim that the redistricting took most of the black and Puerto Rican population in Brooklyn for one thing and carved it up to distribute it in little pieces among contiguous white districts making the black population smaller parts of the larger white population in the white districts as part of a racial gerrymander which would dilute, what otherwise would be considerable political strength held together by a bond of common factors related to race.","start":130.086,"stop":157.568,"duration":27.48},{"text":"I want to make clear that the validity of those charges of racial gerrymander are not before the Court in this case, but the question of whether appellants can have a day in Court, so to speak, to establish the validity of those claims, now what sort of a day that would be is of the essence of this appeal.","start":157.568,"stop":178.05,"duration":20.48},{"text":"The day in Court which appellants sought were the days in Court or before a forum, proper forum which they sought were of three different kinds, all interrelated and again only one of which is here today.","start":178.05,"stop":191.872,"duration":13.82},{"text":"The adverse judgment in the District of Columbia disallowing intervention washed out all possibility of the other two.","start":191.872,"stop":199.95,"duration":8.08},{"text":"The first forum would have been before the Attorney General of the United States under Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act.","start":199.95,"stop":206.295,"duration":6.34},{"text":"When we learned that these voting changes were in process and their implementation were in process --","start":206.295,"stop":210.182,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The time, Mr. Greenberg, last week I think it was, we had a case argued here Georgia versus United States and there was a question of whether Section 5 reached the reapportionments?","start":210.182,"stop":220.771,"duration":10.59}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":220.771,"stop":220.897,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that involved here?","start":220.897,"stop":222.092,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes that is involved here and so far as that is the concerned, the Government takes the same position as we do, but more than that is involved, Mr. Justice Brennan, because also there is the question of whether New York can resume its literacy tests when the 1975 ban expires.","start":222.092,"stop":235.684,"duration":13.59},{"text":"So even if the Georgia case would decide that adversely, this case would still be here with regard to the literacy test.","start":235.684,"stop":241.809,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":241.809,"stop":245.238,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"The first forum in which we sought to appear was before the Attorney General of the United States under Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act.","start":245.238,"stop":252.59,"duration":7.35},{"text":"The appellants communicated with the Attorney General concerning the January and March voting changes and said that when New York submitted its applications for clearance of these voting changes, the appellants wanted to appear as prescribed by the regulations and make representation of these changes were made with the purpose and the effect of racial discrimination.","start":252.59,"stop":278.685,"duration":26.1},{"text":"In fact, the State of New York did submit one set of changes to the Attorney General, but they were sent back as incomplete.","start":278.685,"stop":285.245,"duration":6.56},{"text":"They never sent them back again.","start":285.245,"stop":287.714,"duration":2.47},{"text":"Second, the second forum in which we sought to appear and this opportunity also was washed out by the District of Columbia judgment was in the Southern District of New York, we filed what for the purposes of brevity, I would describe as an Allen type lawsuit, a lawsuit seeking an injunction to compel the State of New York to submit its Voting Rights Act changes to the Attorney General.","start":287.714,"stop":311.161,"duration":23.45},{"text":"And of course, when the District of Columbia judgment was entered, that exempted New York from the requirements of Voting Rights Act so that Allen type lawsuit essentially is wiped out also.","start":311.161,"stop":321.487,"duration":10.33},{"text":"Thirdly, on the day that we filed the lawsuit in New York, we sought to intervene in the pending litigation between New York and the United States in the District Court for the District of Columbia.","start":321.487,"stop":335.77,"duration":14.28},{"text":"Now the United States did not oppose intervention although the State of New York did.","start":335.77,"stop":340.989,"duration":5.22},{"text":"The District Court denied intervention without opinion and granted summary judgment for New York without opinion.","start":340.989,"stop":347.537,"duration":6.55},{"text":"Now appellants have had no hearing before the Attorney General, the appellants have had no hearing in the District Court of New York and appellants have had no hearing from the District Courts of the District of Columbia.","start":347.537,"stop":356.643,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Greenberg, you filed an independent action up in New York challenging the redistricting as such?","start":356.643,"stop":361.996,"duration":5.35}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we did not.","start":361.996,"stop":362.981,"duration":0.99},{"text":"We merely filed an Allen type action in New York urging that the changes should be submitted to the Attorney General of the United States.","start":362.981,"stop":372.736,"duration":9.75},{"text":"The United States, as I read its brief and what it said in this case, does not claim that intervention in cases of this sort never can be allowed and indeed it maybe of some relevance if the United States did not oppose or intervention in the court below.","start":372.736,"stop":386.703,"duration":13.97},{"text":"Rather as I understand the position of the government, it is two parts.","start":386.703,"stop":391.038,"duration":4.34},{"text":"One, that there was no showing of inadequate representation by the United States in the court below and second that the application of the appellants was untimely.","start":391.038,"stop":401.44,"duration":10.4},{"text":"We submit that the record makes clear; one, that representation of the claims of the interveners or the appellants by the United States was indeed inadequate and that it is the timeliness not only where we nearly timely, but the application was filed at the optimum, the best possible time that it could have in the interest of the litigation, in the interest of efficient operation of the Courts, in the interest of the appellant and all the parties.","start":401.44,"stop":428.891,"duration":27.45},{"text":"And finally we claim in the words of Rule 24 that the disposition below quite clearly impaired and impeded the appellant's opportunity to protect their interests.","start":428.891,"stop":439.049,"duration":10.16},{"text":"To demonstrate that there was inadequate representation of our claim below, it is first necessary to describe what that claim is and what adequate representation would have consisted of and how existing representations failed.","start":439.049,"stop":453.628,"duration":14.58},{"text":"We'll first discuss this, then the issue of timeliness and then the issue of how it was --","start":453.628,"stop":458.741,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Greenberg, are you conceding that your claim of intervention invokes only the discretionary?","start":458.741,"stop":466.908,"duration":8.17}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":466.908,"stop":467.657,"duration":0.75},{"text":"This is an application of intervention as of rights.","start":467.657,"stop":469.813,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As of rights, yes.","start":469.813,"stop":471.028,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"This is an application of intervention as of rights and we would submit that we call for squarely under the three principle requirement in that rule, that is inadequate representation, timeliness and impeding or impairment of our interests.","start":471.028,"stop":483.865,"duration":12.84}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But a fortiori, you expect your right of that would also satisfy the (Inaudible)?","start":483.865,"stop":491.534,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly, yes.","start":491.534,"stop":493.295,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And you would say that you did even if you weren't?","start":493.295,"stop":496.647,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":496.647,"stop":497.605,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And acted like this?","start":497.605,"stop":498.677,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and we might take that as a protective position Mr. Justice White, but I think we're so clearly right as to intervention as of right, we have not argued that except to mention it in our brief.","start":498.677,"stop":510.78,"duration":12.1},{"text":"Now as to inadequacy of representation, the claims of the intervenors arose in the Voting Rights Act of 1970 which specifically granted its protection to the black and Puerto Rican voters of Bronx, Kings and New York counties in the State of New York because the amendment specifically and the legislative history demonstrate exhaustively carried out the design of Congress and the administration to present it to vote of Congress, to cover the north as well as the south.","start":510.78,"stop":538.16,"duration":27.38},{"text":"The 1965 law had covered the south.","start":538.16,"stop":540.681,"duration":2.52},{"text":"When time came to extend the law, it was quite clear that the general sentiment of the administration and of Congress was that it would be extended only if were made nationwide and that is what was done and the legislative history is replete with references to the fact that Bronx, Kings and New York county would be covered designed for that very purpose.","start":540.681,"stop":562.109,"duration":21.43},{"text":"Numerous senators and the Attorney Generals so testified.","start":562.109,"stop":566.643,"duration":4.53},{"text":"The formula that covers these counties is that in 1968, they had to view the literacy test and few than 50% of the persons of voting age registered for voting.","start":566.643,"stop":577.608,"duration":10.96},{"text":"That coverage meant two things, when a covered jurisdiction may not use a literacy test while covered by Section 4 and 5 and no changes in the voting laws may be made.","start":577.608,"stop":589.063,"duration":11.46},{"text":"The keywords in the statute and they are in Section 4 which appears in the statutory appendix of our brief is that no such test or devise has been used during the ten years preceding the filing of the action for the purpose or with the effect and I would like to underscore the word effect of denying or bridging the right to vote on account of race and color.","start":589.063,"stop":615.152,"duration":26.09},{"text":"Now the meaning of the words purpose and effect can be found extensively throughout the legislative history and in numerous reported decisions, many of which from this court which was set forth in the brief but for purposes of brevity I am just focusing on one thing about which I think there is no disagreement.","start":615.152,"stop":630.72,"duration":15.57},{"text":"I’d like to talk about this Court’s opinion in Gaston County against the United States.","start":630.72,"stop":636.217,"duration":5.5},{"text":"Meaning of purpose and effect is elucidated in that opinion in several ways that's directly pertinent to this.","start":636.217,"stop":643.999,"duration":7.78},{"text":"Gaston County case decided under the 1965 version of the Voting Rights Act and the 65 version differs from the 70 version only in that, no longer is Gaston County included and southern counties, but that the Congress intended to cover Bronx, Kings and New York counties quite explicitly.","start":643.999,"stop":665.796,"duration":21.8},{"text":"Now the Gaston County case held that the 1965 Act applied to a jurisdiction where non- whites were more illiterate than whites because they had received an inferior education in the county and Justice Harlan’s opinion says that he assumes that they were residents of the county at the time they received their education, but there is a footnote which says “the result would be no different if they had migrated from other counties elsewhere where they had received an education which had caused them to be illiterate.”","start":665.796,"stop":695.074,"duration":29.28},{"text":"And Attorney General Mitchell and numerous senators testified extensively as we have set forth in our brief that that same principle of an inferior education leading to illiteracy or an inferior education in another jurisdiction causing someone to become literate, who then moved to a northern jurisdiction, brings that northern jurisdiction under coverage of the Act.","start":695.074,"stop":719.697,"duration":24.62},{"text":"Now if we just talk briefly about this quite clear aspect of what constitutes effect of racial discrimination, one would think that for there to be adequate representation of the interest of the claimants in the District Court, that should have been brought to the attention of the District Court.","start":719.697,"stop":738.538,"duration":18.84},{"text":"That legal explication of the statute should have been at least presented to the District Court if not urged upon it and such evidence as might be available should have been also presented to the District Court, so that the Court could make a judgment as to whether or not Bronx, Kings and New York county came under the Gaston County decision but that was not done at all and we just say with, one can elaborate under a great deal that if the key legal principle and the available facts, many of which have appeared in our motion to alter judgment when after we were denied intervention, we came back again and said, “look, if you are taking the position that we haven't presented the evidence, we don’t have to present the evidence on a motion to intervene but nevertheless here is at least such of it as we can gather in this brief period of time.","start":738.538,"stop":786.06,"duration":47.52},{"text":"If that available evidence was not also presented to the District Court, then we say that it is inadequate representation, per se, and as a matter of law and as a matter of common sense we just don't see how it can be claimed that there was such a thing as an inadequate --","start":786.06,"stop":800.846,"duration":14.79}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"An adequate representation --","start":800.846,"stop":802.386,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the claim of the interveners.","start":802.386,"stop":807.379,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Why is that an issue in the case whether there was adequate representation?","start":807.379,"stop":810.423,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Because that’s one of the requirements of Rule 24, the intervention rule.","start":810.423,"stop":814.977,"duration":4.55},{"text":"We may intervene if our claims are being inadequately represented, if we come in, in timely fashion and if our ability to present our claims are being impeded.","start":814.977,"stop":825.219,"duration":10.24}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute says -- it says for New York to the United States?","start":825.219,"stop":830.775,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute allows the New York --","start":830.775,"stop":832.108,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute says that the United States have every reason to believe so and so is supposed to accept the judgment?","start":832.108,"stop":837.525,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but the statute does not make New York's concession conclusive as a matter of law and the United States --","start":837.525,"stop":843.922,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The Attorney Generals --","start":843.922,"stop":845.888,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s not – I am sorry, there is no like the attorney general concession, conclusive is a matter of law and the United State concedes --","start":845.888,"stop":851.919,"duration":6.03}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But it doesn't purport to say that the United States is representing a lot of other interests?","start":851.919,"stop":859.772,"duration":7.85}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute doesn't purport to say the United States, but the United States' position in this case and --","start":859.772,"stop":865.136,"duration":5.36}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] if it acts strictly based on the evidence doesn't have reason to believe so and so and concern that there are duties when spoken of the statute.","start":865.136,"stop":880.194,"duration":15.06},{"text":"You may disagree with it but how can you say that they have many obligations to represent here?","start":880.194,"stop":887.175,"duration":6.98}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"The issue is, I would not want to put it in the way whether the United States is derelict in its duty because that sounds some sort of an accusation.","start":887.175,"stop":897.917,"duration":10.74},{"text":"We just say that this action is concluding the rights of the appellants and the interveners and they seek to intervene in the action to assert their rights which is going to be effected by the judgment in this case.","start":897.917,"stop":910.208,"duration":12.29},{"text":"It is not a question of the United States is derelict in its duty, that’s a characterization that is not called for.","start":910.208,"stop":916.315,"duration":6.11}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I know that they are representing it because they have a duty to represent everybody?","start":916.315,"stop":921.306,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well it maybe, I would argue that perhaps though one might assume that they would be representing us until something or the right of the citizens of New York until something appears to the contrary, but certainly the citizens have a right to intervene if they are not being represented.","start":921.306,"stop":938.546,"duration":17.24},{"text":"The United States' action might --","start":938.546,"stop":939.521,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The right to intervene?","start":939.521,"stop":940.629,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right, yes.","start":940.629,"stop":944.558,"duration":3.93},{"text":"Now the Gaston County theory is only part of it, Numerous senators and the Attorney General testified that there is coverage of the statute if there’s a differential literacy rate, if the mere existence and Attorney General Mitchell testified to this, the mere existence of literacy test is a deterrent to registering and voting, quite apart with whether or not there is act of purposeful discrimination and then of course, the matters of unequal education both within or without the jurisdiction.","start":944.558,"stop":977.247,"duration":32.69},{"text":"Nowhere in the investigation or the submission to the court below were these standards explored, where these rules of law present the Court was evidence presented in.","start":977.247,"stop":985.951,"duration":8.7},{"text":"So we submit that the claims of the interveners were not adequately represented and as Justice White pointed out that maybe without regard to what the duty of the United States was in this case, but in any event, the judgment in this case impairs and impedes the rights of the claimants to assert certain claims and that the representation of the United States in this regard with --","start":985.951,"stop":1011.214,"duration":25.26}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that the statute, and you agree that unless the United States generates some reason or believing that as practices it had a discriminatory practice, it's supposed to concern?","start":1011.214,"stop":1029.355,"duration":18.14}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well it may and then of course --","start":1029.355,"stop":1030.633,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that the statute says?","start":1030.633,"stop":1031.81,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes the statute says that.","start":1031.81,"stop":1034.089,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And so that it has itself assessed the evidence and if it feels that it has no reason not to consent it’s supposed to consent?","start":1034.089,"stop":1041.829,"duration":7.74}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"And they maybe totally and I have no doubt or totally objective and sincere in this, but there still may not be an adequate representation of the interest of the claimant?","start":1041.829,"stop":1049.569,"duration":7.74}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You just made this agreement.","start":1049.569,"stop":1051.357,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right.","start":1051.357,"stop":1051.805,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And it has opportunity presented contrary to the Court?","start":1051.805,"stop":1054.372,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I might say as we tried to point out in our reply brief, the brief of the United States is full of a great deal of expression that we have made very serious accusations against.","start":1054.372,"stop":1066.435,"duration":12.06},{"text":"We just said they have been wrong or they might adequately represented us and there is nothing --","start":1066.435,"stop":1070.81,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I know, but I take it from what you now said Mr. Greenberg, on the face of the statute, they didn’t have to represent you and that is why -- if you -- now if you concede that then don’t you automatically satisfy the first requisite of the intervention?","start":1070.81,"stop":1087.31,"duration":16.5}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that would be true and frankly Mr. Justice Brennan, I don’t know whether on the face of the statute they do or they don’t have to represent us in various senses that word might have.","start":1087.31,"stop":1098.729,"duration":11.42},{"text":"One would assume the United States would represent the rights of citizens in the United States with regard to racial discrimination.","start":1098.729,"stop":1103.646,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I know but this statute does provide just as Mr. Justice White said that there is a duty on the United States to consent in certain circumstances?","start":1103.646,"stop":1111.782,"duration":8.14}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and --","start":1111.782,"stop":1112.666,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now if that is so and they may do this independently of any interest of yours, then I ask why don’t you have -- by reason of that haven’t you satisfied the first --","start":1112.666,"stop":1122.372,"duration":9.71}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I would submit we certainly have.","start":1122.372,"stop":1124.334,"duration":1.96},{"text":"I am certainly not going to disagree with that but the fact is, whatever their duty might be and it’s not entirely clear in the face of the statute.","start":1124.334,"stop":1132.982,"duration":8.65},{"text":"In this particular case, they did not presented or argued the court below the relevant facts in the law.","start":1132.982,"stop":1139.55,"duration":6.57},{"text":"That’s the timeliness I would just like to say a word and that is the brief reduces to a battle of our affidavits and their assertions to the brief as to what one lawyer said to another and in my experience at least, that kind of dispute is quite common place in nobody's line.","start":1139.55,"stop":1157.466,"duration":17.92},{"text":"It’s just a question of subjective interpretation of what was meant and issues of this sort should be determined wherever possible on objective grounds and we can see no more timely filing that was then within two days after having learned of the United States consent and four days of the actual filing of the consent.","start":1157.466,"stop":1176.562,"duration":19.1},{"text":"Certainly, we couldn’t have filed before they filed their consent or very well might have been premature because we didn’t know what their position is going to be.","start":1176.562,"stop":1184.217,"duration":7.66},{"text":"Having filled their consent coming into court within four days --","start":1184.217,"stop":1186.857,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you have thought Mr. Greenberg that you would have been fully as entitled to intervene before they filed their consent as after?","start":1186.857,"stop":1196.428,"duration":9.57},{"text":"I think they could be making the same argument if you had filed before?","start":1196.428,"stop":1200.23,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Jack Greenberg","textObjs":[{"text":"I think we might have been, but I think that if we had come in earlier and the Court said, “Well, how do you know that they’re not going to urge exactly all of your positions upon us,” we might then argue that we represent ourselves better.","start":1200.23,"stop":1213.218,"duration":12.99},{"text":"We have done a more exhaustive examination, we don’t know what they’ve done and so forth but certainly I would think the optimum time to file would be when their position has become manifest.","start":1213.218,"stop":1224.374,"duration":11.16},{"text":"At least I would urge that and I would think that it would have been perhaps an unnecessary burden on the Court and to come in with an intervention before their position become manifest.","start":1224.374,"stop":1234.917,"duration":10.54},{"text":"New York argues that this would have disrupted the primary process, but of course, that is hardly necessary.","start":1234.917,"stop":1244.673,"duration":9.76},{"text":"The Court could have required an accelerated hearing.","start":1244.673,"stop":1248.392,"duration":3.72},{"text":"It could have required the lawsuit to go on while a primary process was going on, to put one on simultaneously.","start":1248.392,"stop":1255.317,"duration":6.92},{"text":"It could have made moderate adjustments in the dates.","start":1255.317,"stop":1256.978,"duration":1.66},{"text":"These are common place problems with regard to voting cases.","start":1256.978,"stop":1260.161,"duration":3.18},{"text":"What the Court could have done what will happen here if petitioners or appellants are to prevail on this appeal make any ruling apply to a later elections so that the disruption of the primary process is not a substantial argument.","start":1260.161,"stop":1273.34,"duration":13.18},{"text":"More of which we pointed out that to the extent if there is any inconvenience, we have to look at the fact that New York waited 18 months after the Voting Act was passed and nine months after the Attorney General said that it was covered to even file its action, then he gave the United States 90 days.","start":1273.34,"stop":1289.598,"duration":16.26},{"text":"If you look at all the different time sequences in this case, the time between various acts, the four days within which we acted is a small fraction of the time that anybody else took to do anything at all.","start":1289.598,"stop":1300.165,"duration":10.57},{"text":"I like to reserve the balance of my time.","start":1300.165,"stop":1307.756,"duration":7.59}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Randolph.","start":1307.756,"stop":1311.675,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"Raymond Randolph Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":1311.675,"stop":1313.527,"duration":1.85},{"text":"I would like to respond first of all, to counsel's suggestion that what this Court could do on remand is send this case back for the District Court to consider their motion to intervene while the leaving the 1972 election results in New York in effect.","start":1313.527,"stop":1330.42,"duration":16.89},{"text":"I would point out that that does not require any action by this Court.","start":1330.42,"stop":1334.812,"duration":4.39},{"text":"The substance of what Mr. Greenberg suggests and I will direct the Court’s attention now to Section 4 on page, essay 2 of their brief which is the effect white brief and you’ll notice in the first full paragraph, the second sentence says, “the Court shall retain jurisdiction of any action pursuant to this subsection for five years after judgment.”","start":1334.812,"stop":1364.362,"duration":29.55}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"What page again?","start":1364.362,"stop":1365.592,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Raymond Randolph Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Essay two Mr. Chief Justice.","start":1365.592,"stop":1367.746,"duration":2.15},{"text":"It’s the appendix to their brief and I am pointing now to the first full paragraph at the top of the page, second sentence.","start":1367.746,"stop":1380.437,"duration":12.69},{"text":"The Court shall retain jurisdiction of any action pursuing to the subsection after judgment.”","start":1380.437,"stop":1385.762,"duration":5.33},{"text":"The second part of that sentence allows the Attorney General to reopen the case at any time within five years.","start":1385.762,"stop":1392.911,"duration":7.15},{"text":"Now --","start":1392.911,"stop":1394.476,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"It won't do him any good if he’s been denied leave to intervene already?","start":1394.476,"stop":1398.377,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Raymond Randolph Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it does him some good in the sense that, I think they can renew their motion to intervene at any time within this five year period.","start":1398.377,"stop":1406.097,"duration":7.72},{"text":"It’s simply like a consent judgment in an antitrust case where people intervene after the consent judgment is entered.","start":1406.097,"stop":1412.388,"duration":6.29},{"text":"The potential disruption to New York’s 1972 elections has now passed as Mr. Greenberg himself has suggested.","start":1412.388,"stop":1419.786,"duration":7.4},{"text":"We believe that was the primary reason why the District Court denied intervention at the time that it did.","start":1419.786,"stop":1425.251,"duration":5.46},{"text":"The second thing is that the 4A judgment is now outstanding.","start":1425.251,"stop":1428.872,"duration":3.62},{"text":"Now this is not in the record, but I understand councilmanic districts have been changed.","start":1428.872,"stop":1433.201,"duration":4.33},{"text":"I think counsel from New York will talk about this in New York.","start":1433.201,"stop":1437.489,"duration":4.29},{"text":"So that since the 4A judgment is now outstanding, that is exempting New York, there won’t be a disruption of elections in the future while the appellants' motion is determined and the timeliness problem which we consider from the point of view of not only how long has this action been pending but what effect would allowing intervention at this time have on the State of New York.","start":1437.489,"stop":1460.937,"duration":23.45},{"text":"It’s not longer a critical problem.","start":1460.937,"stop":1463.6,"duration":2.66},{"text":"Now I can’t say what position the United States would take if they renew their motion to intervene.","start":1463.6,"stop":1468.839,"duration":5.24},{"text":"We didn’t object before but I think that in line with Mr. Greenberg’s suggestion that what the Court should do in this case is just send it back to the District Court and allow the 72 elections to remain in effect while the same result can be accomplished simply by the provisions of the statute itself.","start":1468.839,"stop":1487.338,"duration":18.5},{"text":"The other point I would like to make is that although appellants have said in their brief, “if we can’t intervene here, under what conceivable circumstances can anyone,” I think really misstates and misconceives the problem here because what they are contending for is intervention as of right.","start":1487.338,"stop":1503.698,"duration":16.36},{"text":"There is always permissive intervention and that is a much a easier process to urge upon the Court because the only requirement is the claim that they have is as in common with a question of fact or law in the main action and that’s even if they have no right to intervene which is not our position in this case, it still leaves them the opportunity to seek permissive intervention.","start":1503.698,"stop":1529.584,"duration":25.89}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What are you suggesting that we not decide this case but let it go back?","start":1529.584,"stop":1533.527,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Raymond Randolph Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the issue before this Court is quite simply, did the District Court err in April of 1972 in denying intervention to appellants at that time in light of the fact that the New York and I will go through the sequence of events --","start":1533.527,"stop":1548.634,"duration":15.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What you’re suggesting is, as I understood it, if we sustained that position --","start":1548.634,"stop":1554.144,"duration":5.51}]},{"speakerName":"Raymond Randolph Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1554.144,"stop":1554.303,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- sustained the lower court, you are saying it is meaningless anyway because they can go back and do it all over again?","start":1554.303,"stop":1559.45,"duration":5.15}]},{"speakerName":"Raymond Randolph Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I’m saying as without prejudice to the appellants to renew their motion to intervene, the difference is --","start":1559.45,"stop":1564.877,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right and then the issues then of intervention of right or permissive intervention that arise again?","start":1564.877,"stop":1573.474,"duration":8.6}]},{"speakerName":"Raymond Randolph Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it would depend on their claims, but we have -- our position in this case really, our position is we have assumed a number of things.","start":1573.474,"stop":1580.396,"duration":6.92},{"text":"First of all, we didn’t object below to their intervening.","start":1580.396,"stop":1583.241,"duration":2.85},{"text":"We consider this a matter of discretion with the District Court because of the time it was filed.","start":1583.241,"stop":1587.521,"duration":4.28},{"text":"That was New York’s problem, they had a primary election coming up, nominating petition circulating the entire thing would have been through a haywire, but we have argued this case on the basis that their application at that time was not timely.","start":1587.521,"stop":1601.269,"duration":13.75},{"text":"Now the difference would be if they now filed under Section 4A.","start":1601.269,"stop":1605.723,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You wouldn't have that argument.","start":1605.723,"stop":1607.514,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Raymond Randolph Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That argument would not be present.","start":1607.514,"stop":1608.731,"duration":1.22},{"text":"We didn’t object before.","start":1608.731,"stop":1610.21,"duration":1.48},{"text":"I can’t commit as to what position we take.","start":1610.21,"stop":1612.65,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Might a Court not hold a permissive intervener to stricter time requirement into an intervener as a bright that that being that it really doesn’t have to get in anyway and therefore your resolve time judgments against him whereas in the case of intervention of right you may allow more latches?","start":1612.65,"stop":1634.312,"duration":21.66}]},{"speakerName":"Raymond Randolph Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That maybe true, I think that’s probably true, I think that the opinions may not state that, but I think that the gist of them is along these lines, Mr. Justice and in fact, under permissive intervention, the Court wanted to exercise its discretion is required to consider whether the intervention would delay or prejudice the adjudication parties in the case.","start":1634.312,"stop":1655.492,"duration":21.18}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I understand you to imply at least not say that they can go back now in a permissive intervention and get everything that this Court could give them?","start":1655.492,"stop":1666.582,"duration":11.09}]},{"speakerName":"Raymond Randolph Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that would be a matter for the District Court to determine. One of the problem -- we don’t have an opinion here.","start":1666.582,"stop":1672.235,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well but of course, that if they go back and if they get it, they would have had everything that this Court can give.","start":1672.235,"stop":1677.627,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"Raymond Randolph Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"With one exception, with one important exception which now Mr. Greenberg has told us they wouldn’t get anyway, which is that they would not have held up the 1972 elections in New York.","start":1677.627,"stop":1687.819,"duration":10.19},{"text":"If one reads the papers in this case, if you read their motion to affirm, there’s not a mention of what the issue is in this case which is about New York’s literacy test or whether New York had applied that discriminatorily in the past years.","start":1687.819,"stop":1699.368,"duration":11.55},{"text":"I direct the Court’s attention to that.","start":1699.368,"stop":1701.364,"duration":2},{"text":"All it talks about is the New York primary elections.","start":1701.364,"stop":1704.803,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will resume there in the morning.","start":1704.803,"stop":1708.277,"duration":3.47}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Feb  27 - 28, 1973","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"72-129","citation":"413 US 345 (1973)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/413/345","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 21, 1973"}